\chapter{Structure sheaf as a sheaf of abelian groups, sheafification and Ext}
\label{chap:Cohomology_StructureSheafAb}

This chapter executes Phase~A steps~2--4 of \texttt{STRATEGY.md} on the topology of opens of an arbitrary topological space, using the \lstinline{HasSheafCompose} instance of Chapter~\ref{chap:Cohomology_SheafCompose} as input. It supplies three pieces of infrastructure that sit immediately upstream of Definition~\ref{def:genus} (the genus of a smooth proper curve):

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \texttt{HasSheafify} for $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued sheaves on $\opens X$ (Phase~A step~2).
  \item \texttt{HasExt} on the same sheaf category (Phase~A step~3).
  \item Promotion of the structure sheaf $\struct C$ from $\CommRingCat$-valued to $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued, packaging the data on which \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Sheaf.H} can be evaluated (Phase~A step~4 first half).
\end{enumerate}

A discovery probe of Mathlib \texttt{b80f227} (logged in \texttt{task\_pending.md}) confirms that all three pieces are constructible directly from existing Mathlib API plus the iteration~004 \lstinline{HasSheafCompose} instance: no new mathematical content is introduced here, only the typeclass plumbing and one definition. After this chapter lands, the only remaining steps in Phase~A are equipping $H^1(C, \struct C)$ with a $k$-vector-space structure and proving Serre finiteness; both are deferred to subsequent iterations.

The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and instance here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of $H^1(C, \struct C)$ in Definition~\ref{def:genus}.

\section{Sheafification of $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued sheaves on opens}

\begin{theorem}[Sheafification on the topology of opens, $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued]
  \label{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_AddCommGrp}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Cohomology.instHasSheafify_Opens_AddCommGrp}
  Let $X$ be a topological space. Then the Grothendieck topology of opens of $X$ has
  \[
    \mathtt{HasSheafify}(\opens(X), \AddCommGrpCat).
  \]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Mathlib's general sheafification API constructs \lstinline{HasSheafify J A} whenever \lstinline{HasWeakSheafify J A} holds and the resulting sheafification preserves finite limits. For \lstinline{J = Opens.grothendieckTopology X} and \lstinline{A = AddCommGrpCat} both prerequisites are already wired in Mathlib (concrete-category sheafification on a small site, plus exactness of $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued sheafification on a Noetherian-style topology). The instance is therefore inferable; the prover's task is to establish the universe pinning needed to make \lstinline{infer_instance} succeed.
\end{proof}

\section{$\Ext$ for sheaves on opens}

\begin{theorem}[$\Ext$ on the topology of opens, $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued]
  \label{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_AddCommGrp}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Cohomology.instHasExt_Sheaf_Opens_AddCommGrp}
  \uses{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_AddCommGrp}
  Let $X$ be a topological space. Then the category $\Sheaf(\opens(X), \AddCommGrpCat)$ has
  \[
    \mathtt{HasExt.\{u+1\}}\bigl(\Sheaf(\opens(X), \AddCommGrpCat)\bigr).
  \]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  $\AddCommGrpCat$ is abelian. The sheaf category $\Sheaf(J, A)$ inherits an abelian structure from an abelian $A$ once \lstinline{HasSheafify J A} holds (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_AddCommGrp}). Mathlib's \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasExt.standard} produces a \lstinline{HasExt} instance from any abelian category. The universe annotation \lstinline{HasExt.\{u+1\}} matches the unique morphism universe of \lstinline{Sheaf (Opens.gT X) AddCommGrpCat.\{u\}}, which lives at type-universe \lstinline{u+1}; the sheafification API forces this shape.
\end{proof}

\section{Structure sheaf as a sheaf of abelian groups}

\begin{definition}[Structure sheaf as a sheaf of abelian groups]
  \label{def:Scheme_toAbSheaf}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toAbSheaf}
  \uses{thm:HasSheafCompose_forget}
  Let $C$ be a scheme. The structure sheaf of $C$, viewed as a sheaf of abelian groups on the topology of opens of the underlying topological space of $C$, is
  \[
    \toAbSheaf(C) \;:=\; (\sheafCompose(\opens(\Csp), F_{\mathrm{forget}})).\mathtt{obj}\;C.\mathtt{sheaf} \;\in\; \Sheaf(\opens(\Csp), \AddCommGrpCat),
  \]
  where $\Csp$ is the underlying topological space of $C$, $C.\mathtt{sheaf} \in \Sheaf(\opens(\Csp), \CommRingCat)$ is the Mathlib structure sheaf, and $F_{\mathrm{forget}} = \forget_2 \CommRingCat \RingCat \circ \forget_2 \RingCat \AddCommGrpCat$ is the forget composite of Chapter~\ref{chap:Cohomology_SheafCompose}.
\end{definition}

The construction uses \lstinline{CategoryTheory.sheafCompose}, which requires the \lstinline{HasSheafCompose} instance from Chapter~\ref{chap:Cohomology_SheafCompose}. Functoriality in $C$ is delegated to a future iteration once we need it for naturality of the cohomology long exact sequence.

\section{Use in the project}

The chain $\HasSheafCompose \to \HasSheafify \to \HasExt \to \toAbSheaf$ unblocks the abelian-group-level definition of $H^n(C, \struct C)$:
\[
  H^n(C, \struct C) \;:=\; \toAbSheaf(C).\mathtt{H}\,n,
\]
where \lstinline{Sheaf.H} is the abstract sheaf-cohomology API of Mathlib's \lstinline{Sites/SheafCohomology/Basic.lean}. The result is automatically an \lstinline{AddCommGroup} via \lstinline{Sheaf.instAddCommGroupH}. Only two steps remain inside Phase~A:

\begin{itemize}
  \item Equip $H^1(C, \struct C)$ with the $k$-module structure inherited from the $k$-algebra structure on $\Gamma(C, \struct C)$ (Phase~A step~5).
  \item Establish $\Module.\finrank$ finiteness via Serre's theorem on coherent cohomology of proper $k$-schemes (Phase~A step~6 / "finiteness").
\end{itemize}

Both are deferred to iterations beyond this chapter.

\section{Mathlib gap}

Mathlib \texttt{b80f227} carries every constituent piece needed for this chapter:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasSheafify} and the small-site / concrete-category sheafification API for $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued sheaves on $\opens(X)$ (verified by \texttt{lean\_run\_code}: \lstinline{infer_instance} succeeds for \lstinline{HasSheafify (Opens.grothendieckTopology X) AddCommGrpCat.\{u\}}).
  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasExt.standard} for any abelian category, and the abelian instance \lstinline{Sheaf.instAbelian} on $\Sheaf(J, \AddCommGrpCat)$ (verified by \texttt{lean\_run\_code}).
  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.sheafCompose} together with the \lstinline{HasSheafCompose} instance of Chapter~\ref{chap:Cohomology_SheafCompose} (closed in iteration~004).
  \item The structure sheaf \lstinline{Scheme.sheaf : Sheaf (Opens.grothendieckTopology X.toTopCat) CommRingCat} is built into the Mathlib \lstinline{Scheme} structure.
\end{itemize}

Nothing is genuinely missing for this chapter; the work is to assemble the typeclass plumbing with universe annotations chosen so that downstream \lstinline{Sheaf.H} consumers can reach the sheaf via \lstinline{infer_instance}.

\chapter{The relative Picard functor as an abelian-group-valued presheaf}
\label{chap:Picard_FunctorAb}

This chapter is the natural successor to Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}. The Lean realisation of the relative Picard functor in Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} is $\Type$-valued (\lstinline{(Over (Spec k))ᵒᵖ ⥤ Type u}); the construction merely forgets the abelian-group structure that the values $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ carry by definition. To set up Phase~C step~3 (étale sheafification, deferred) and any future cohomology-of-Picard-presheaf work, we need an $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued variant whose values agree on the nose with the $\Type$-valued ones.

The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supporting Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian} via the same path as Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}.

\section{Definition}

\begin{definition}[Relative Picard functor, abelian-group valued]
  \label{def:Pic_functorAb}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb}
  \uses{def:Pic_functor}
  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. The \emph{abelian-group-valued relative Picard functor} of $C$ over $k$ is the contravariant functor
  \[
    \PicardFunctorAb\, C \;\colon\; (\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}} \;\longrightarrow\; \AddCommGrpCat,\qquad
    S \;\longmapsto\; \mathtt{AddCommGrpCat.of}\;\bigl(\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)\bigr),
  \]
  with morphisms induced by \lstinline{PicardFunctor.quotMap} (defined in Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}) wrapped as \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat} morphisms via \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat.ofHom}.
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}
  The underlying-set functor of $\PicardFunctorAb\, C$ agrees on the nose with the $\Type$-valued Picard functor of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}: Definition~\ref{def:Pic_functor} computes the same group quotient $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ but discards the group structure. The lemma \lstinline{PicardFunctorAb.forget_eq} (or analogous) records this: \lstinline{PicardFunctorAb C ⋙ forget AddCommGrpCat = PicardFunctor C} (up to natural iso). It is needed to transport later results (e.g.\ representability) between the two flavours.
\end{remark}

\section{Use in the project}

Definition~\ref{def:Pic_functorAb} sets up the codomain needed for:

\begin{itemize}
  \item Étale sheafification of the relative Picard functor (Phase~C step~3, deferred). The sheafification API \lstinline{CategoryTheory.presheafToSheaf} requires an $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued presheaf to land in $\Sheaf(J, \AddCommGrpCat)$.
  \item Comparison with the Jacobian's $\Pic^0$ as a group scheme: the connected-component-of-identity of the representing scheme is a group object in $\Sch_k$; identifying $\PicardFunctorAb \cong \mathrm{HomFunctor}(\Pic_{C/k})$ via Yoneda is the cleanest path to the four \lstinline{Jacobian.lean} sorries.
  \item Direct definition of $H^n$-of-the-Picard-presheaf if a future iteration wants to expose it as a derived functor.
\end{itemize}

The representability theorem \ref{thm:Pic_representable} of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} carries over verbatim once the étale sheafification of $\PicardFunctorAb$ has been constructed (Phase~C step~3); the four \lstinline{Jacobian.lean} sorries are the same as before. This chapter does \emph{not} add a representability theorem of its own — the present chapter is purely the codomain change.

\section{Mathlib gap}

Mathlib \texttt{b80f227} has every constituent for this chapter:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat.of}, \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat.ofHom} for wrapping a group / homomorphism into the bundled categorical shape.
  \item \lstinline{CommGroup} structure on \lstinline{Pic _ ⧸ _} via Mathlib's quotient-of-commutative-group machinery.
  \item This project's \lstinline{Picard.Functor} (Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}, closed in iteration~004) for the underlying construction and the \lstinline{quotMap} functoriality.
\end{itemize}

The chapter therefore introduces no new sorries beyond the single definition itself; the prover task is to wrap the Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} construction in \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat} and discharge the resulting \lstinline{map\_id}/\lstinline{map\_comp} obligations (which reduce to those already proved for \lstinline{quotMap}).

\section{Forward-compatibility note}

The abelian-group-valued variant inherits the \lstinline{LineBundle} approximation from Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}: the values on non-affine $S$ are smaller subgroups of the true relative Picard group. Étale sheafification of $\PicardFunctorAb$ would compose with this approximation on the codomain side; closing the eventual étale-sheafified representability sorry on the approximation is forbidden for the same reason as in Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}. The deferred \lstinline{representable} of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} is the unique gating obstruction; this chapter neither widens nor narrows it.
